<p><b>Types of relationships: -</b> 
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>1. Competition: -</b><br> Discussed above.
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>2. Mutualism: -</b><br> Mutualism is a relationship in which organisms benefit from each other. This is a positive, positive relationship.
<br>An example of this would be the bee and the flower. The bee gets nectar and honey from the flower. The bee contributes back to the flower by spreading the pollen so that the flowers can reproduce.
<p style="text-align: right">(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecological_relationship) 

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>3. Parasitism: -</b><br> Parasitism is a relationship in which one organism (the parasite) benefits while the other (the host) is harmed. This is a positive, negative relationship. The parasite usually lives on or inside the other organism. For example, mosquito is a parasite, feeding on a human while transferring the disease called Malaria. Another example would be the sun fish and the organisms that live in their skin (The Blue Planet), or a tick or fleas that lives off of a dog. Similarly, lice are an example of parasitism because they feed on blood from the humans head.

\image image7
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 7. Mosquito sucking blood

\image image8
<p style="text-align: center">Fig. 8. Parasites on a caterpillar
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>4. Predation: -</b><br> Discussed above.
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>5. Defense: -</b><br> The act of an organism to save itself from becoming a prey of another organism. 

