<p><b>Coevolution and introduction of species: -</b>
<p>The term coevolution is used to describe cases where two (or more) species reciprocally affect each other's evolution.
<p>In biology, coevolution is "the change of a biological object triggered by the change of a related object."
<p>For example, an evolutionary change in the morphology of a plant, might affect the morphology of an herbivore that eats the plant, which in turn might affect the evolution of the plant, which might affect the evolution of the herbivore...and so on.
<p>Coevolution is likely to happen when different species have close ecological interactions with one another. These ecological relationships include:
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. Predator/prey and parasite/host
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. Competitive species
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3. Mutualistic species
<p style="text-align: right">(http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evosite/evo101/IIIFCoevolution.shtml)